Interview Questions
1) How to perform multiple tasks by multiple threads?
-->Multiple tasks can be performed simultaneously by creating multiple threads.

Each thread executes its own run() method independently.

Example
class Task1 extends Thread {

    public void run() {

        for(int i=1; i<=5; i++) {

            System.out.println("Task 1");
        }
    }
}

class Task2 extends Thread {

    public void run() {

        for(int i=1; i<=5; i++) {

            System.out.println("Task 2");
        }
    }
}

class Demo {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Task1 t1 = new Task1();

        Task2 t2 = new Task2();

        t1.start();

        t2.start();
    }
  }
  Explanation
    t1 executes Task1
    t2 executes Task2
    Both tasks run concurrently



2) How to perform multiple tasks by a single thread?
-->
    Multiple tasks can be performed by a single thread by calling multiple methods inside the same run() method.
    
    Example
    class MyThread extends Thread {
    
        public void task1() {
    
            System.out.println("Task 1");
        }
    
        public void task2() {
    
            System.out.println("Task 2");
        }
    
        public void run() {
    
            task1();
    
            task2();
        }
    }
    
    class Demo {
    
        public static void main(String[] args) {
    
            MyThread t = new MyThread();
    
            t.start();
        }
    }
    Explanation
        
        Single thread executes:
        
        task1()
        task2()
        
        one after another sequentially.



3) Can a thread execute multiple run() methods?
-->No, a thread cannot execute multiple run() methods simultaneously.

A thread can have only one active run() method.

However, inside one run() method, we can call multiple methods.

Example
class MyThread extends Thread {

    public void task1() {

        System.out.println("Task 1");
    }

    public void task2() {

        System.out.println("Task 2");
    }

    public void run() {

        task1();

        task2();
    }
}
Important Point

Java does not allow:

public void run()
public void run(int x)

for thread execution separately.

Only:

public void run()

is treated as thread execution method.



4) What is a single-threaded model vs multi-threaded model?
-->
| Single-Threaded Model                  | Multi-Threaded Model             |
| -------------------------------------- | -------------------------------- |
| Only one thread executes tasks         | Multiple threads execute tasks   |
| Tasks execute sequentially             | Tasks execute concurrently       |
| Slow performance                       | Better performance               |
| CPU utilization is low                 | Better CPU utilization           |
| If one task waits, whole program waits | Other threads continue execution |
| Simple to design                       | More complex                     |

5) How can anonymous inner classes or lambda expressions be used to create and run threads in Java? Explain with an example.
-->Using Anonymous Inner Class
We can create a thread without creating a separate class.
Example
class Demo {    public static void main(String[] args) {        Thread t = new Thread() {            public void run() {                System.out.println("Thread Running");            }        };        t.start();    }}

Using Lambda Expression
Since Runnable is a functional interface, lambda expressions can be used.
Example
class Demo {  
    public static void main(String[] args) {  
        Runnable r = () -> {           
                System.out.println("Thread Running");        
    };      

    Thread t = new Thread(r);     
    t.start(); 
    
    }
}

Advantages of Lambda Threads


Less code


Cleaner syntax


Easy readability


Commonly used in modern Java applications

